WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.220
All right, I'm going to talk about emerging therapies and CMML, which has kind of been

00:00:08.220 --> 00:00:09.300
long overlooked.

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:15.060
And we'll kind of first go over the DAKOTA trial.

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:18.100
So I'm sure many of you are familiar with the DAKOTA trial.

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:22.620
It was the first randomized phase three trial specifically for CMML.

00:00:23.020 --> 00:00:29.920
This trial enrolled patients with myeloproliferative CMML, which is defined as patients who had

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:32.060
a white blood cell count over 13,000.

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:39.680
And they had to have either extramedullary disease or two or more criteria amongst those

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:43.020
that are listed kind of indicating higher risk disease.

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:49.680
They were randomized one-to-one to either hydroxyurea or to dacitabine.

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:54.820
And the primary endpoint of the DAKOTA trial was event-free survival, which was defined

00:00:54.820 --> 00:00:59.220
as death, second transformation to secondary AML or CMML.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:08.220
And so, again, I'm sure many of you are familiar with the results of the DAKOTA trial, which

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:17.280
basically showed no difference in terms of EFS or OS between hydroxyurea and dacitabine.

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:29.280
However, there was a signal of increased progression or AML transformation in the hydroxyurea

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:32.460
arm compared to the dacitabine arm.

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:37.380
However, this was sort of outweighed by early toxicity in the dacitabine arm.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:41.140
So it ended up that there was no real survival benefit seen.

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:45.500
So, again, this is kind of the takeaway from the DAKOTA study.

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:52.060
There were superior response rates with dacitabine, but toxicity may have masked a survival benefit.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:58.880
So kind of interestingly, this was just published in Leukemia.

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:05.000
Showing that there is a role, perhaps, for cytoreduction in proliferative CMML.

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:08.480
So this is a post hoc analysis from the DAKOTA trial.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:17.040
And basically, what the authors showed was that if you look at the patient's blood counts

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:23.340
at cycle six, these are the blood counts from the patients enrolled in the DAKOTA trial at

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:29.600
cycle six, if they had an absolute monocyte count less than 1,000 and a white blood cell count less

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:38.020
than 10,000, they actually had superior overall survival compared to those who had elevated absolute

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:43.640
monocyte counts or white blood cell count over 10,000, and this was regardless of treatment.

00:02:43.640 --> 00:02:50.220
So this is interesting data basically telling us that there may be a survival benefit associated

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:56.180
with cytoreduction of monocytes and immature granulocytes in CMML that is treatment independent.

00:02:56.180 --> 00:02:59.520
So very similar to the paradigm in the classical

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:07.620
MPNs where you have cytoreduction and you are able to kind of modulate survival to an extent.

00:03:07.620 --> 00:03:14.300
And there was also shown to be an improvement in overall survival and also

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:23.820
decreased transformation to AML at the cycle three, after cycle three, if patients had

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:29.440
lower classical monocyte counts or lower immature granulocyte counts after cycle

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:36.960
C, after cycle three. So again, suggesting that cytoreduction could be important in CMML

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:41.840
and improve survival irrespective of how you cytoreduce patients.

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:52.400
Okay. So this is data from ASH 2025. This is another randomized trial,

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:59.360
this time in MDS MPN. So this included CMML patients, but also patients with any of the other

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:06.960
MDS MPNs, excluding GMML. So this is an adult trial. And so in this trial, which is the MOUK

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:15.120
trial, they're randomizing patients two to one to Roldesidabine versus Hydroxyurea. And the

00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:22.320
enrollment criteria are not quite exactly the same as in Dakota, but you're kind of trying to

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:28.880
select for patients who have a more proliferative phenotype or higher risk disease. And so this is a

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:34.400
trial design. These patients are treated for six cycles with either Roldesidabine versus

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:38.560
Hydroxyurea and then assessed for a response. So primary endpoint is

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:46.880
best response at cycle six using the MDS MPN criteria from 2015.

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:58.000
And so responses are kind of defined as clinical benefit or better. And so this is actually the

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:09.760
first trial to show an improvement in overall survival in MDS MPN. So this trial, the MOUK trial,

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:16.480
does show an improvement in overall survival with Roldesidabine, 24.2 months compared to

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:23.600
Hydroxyurea, 17 months. And the response rates were about twice as high with Roldesidabine

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.920
compared to Hydroxyurea as well. And so if you look at the CMML subgroups,

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:33.200
specifically, you also see the same trends. You see improved overall survival, progression-free

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:39.280
survival, and AML-free survival with Roldesidabine versus Hydroxyurea. So

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:45.920
this is something I would consider an evolving standard of care for CMML.

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:52.720
Most of the patients in Dakota and this trial did require dose reductions. As

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:57.840
some of you probably know, Roldesidabine can be quite myelosuppressive. But again,

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:04.560
this is the first trial that's demonstrating a survival benefit in MDS MPN. And, you know,

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:11.120
most of these patients were CMML patients. So I want to talk a little bit about MEK inhibition.

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:21.680
So this is actually an IIT that I developed that's open at Huntsman, OHSU, and Fred Hutch.

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:27.360
So this is a trial, it's a phase two trial of cobimetinib, which is an oral MEK inhibitor as a

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:33.360
therapy, in patients with CMML who have RAS or MAP kinase-activating mutations

00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:38.480
at a VAF of 5% or greater. So it's not just KRAS and NRAS, but it also includes

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:42.480
other sympathetic mutations that activate the RAS/MAP kinase signaling pathway.

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:48.880
And we have two cohorts, untreated CMML and CMML patients who have been HMA-exposed,

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:56.160
and we're giving them cobimetinib phase one through 21 of a 28-day cycle for up to a year.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:04.880
So this was opened at Huntsman in 2021 and later at Fred Hutch and OHSU. We were able to enroll 14

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:11.920
patients. It was hard to accrue. We closed to accrual in December of 2025, so very recently

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:18.560
here. And that was primarily because Genentech is no longer manufacturing cobimetinib for use in

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:27.600
clinical studies. The primary endpoint is overall response rate by MDS MPN criteria. And we're seeing

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:34.320
50% response rate in the newly diagnosed cohort and about a 25% response rate in the HMA-exposed

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:39.680
cohort. Of course, these are small numbers. But we've also done single-cell RNA-seq of

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:45.920
longitudinal samples. We're currently analyzing this data and hoping to publish it later this

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:50.400
year. But I want to go on and talk about some other agents that are under active

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:57.520
investigation in CMML. So we actually use rexalitinib in CMML quite a bit. And

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:03.040
that's not because CMML is associated with JAK2 mutations, but it is because

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:10.960
CMML is explicitly sensitive to GM-CSF signaling, which you can block with JAK2 inhibition.

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:15.600
So JAK2 mutations actually only occur in 5% to 10% of CMML patients.

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:20.160
There was a phase one study of rex in CMML that enrolled 20 patients,

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:27.440
both untreated and HMA-exposed. Rexalitinib was pretty well tolerated, kind of the typical side

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:33.360
effect profiles that you might see in MPN. There were spleen responses, and there were some

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:39.600
hemologic improvements. There was not symptomatic improvement, although this was noted clinically,

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:44.480
and that might just have been because the pros were not appropriate for use in this population.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.400
There was no association between response in any single cytokine level in patient plasma samples.

00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:56.880
However, because there did seem to be clinical benefit, this is being studied in a phase two

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:03.280
clinical trial currently, with a phase two dose being 20 milligrams twice daily.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:11.200
And so this was last reported on in ASH 2023. Notably, 70% of these patients had proliferative

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:20.320
CMML. And according to the MDS-MPN response criteria, 66% of patients actually did have

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:27.280
clinical benefit, and 30% of patients did have, you know, spleen volume reduction over

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:33.680
at least or over 35%. And we saw symptom improvement using the MPN-SAF-PSS score.

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:41.440
This has led to kind of interest in developing other JAK2 inhibitors in CMML. So there are two

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:50.000
new studies of procretinib in CMML. And procretinib may end up having greater efficacy because, as

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:57.200
you guys probably know, it's also a FLT3 inhibitor. It's an IRAC1 inhibitor. And it can also inhibit a

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:05.120
CBR1, so potentially improving anemia responses as well. So there's a phase one, two trial that's

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:11.280
open at Mount Sinai, looking at procretinib in combination with AZA. And then there's also this

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:19.040
phase two PROSPERA trial that's looking at procretinib in combination versus, sorry,

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:27.120
procretinib versus hydroxyurea. Lenzilumab is an antibody that neutralizes GMC-SF,

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:34.960
this has been studied in CMML as well in a phase one trial. It's dose IV. And, you know,

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:42.480
the overall response rate by MBS MPN criteria was only 27%. But there did seem to be a signal

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:48.800
in patients who had RAS pathway mutations. And so this kind of led to the PREACH-M phase two,

00:10:48.800 --> 00:10:57.040
three trial in Australia, looking at AZA in combination with lenzilumab. And, you know, the

00:10:57.040 --> 00:11:03.440
responses from this trial were actually pretty impressive in CMML. So there were 32 patients

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:12.240
enrolled on a len-AZA arm, and 86% of them achieved a CR or optimal marrow CR within the

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:19.040
first 12 months by the overlap criteria. So it's very hard to achieve, you know, CRs

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:26.960
using these criteria. So I'm curious to see this, the results when it's published, because

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:33.600
it's almost too good to believe. There was a high rate of decreases in mutational subclones

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:40.480
in the study as well, and it was well tolerated. Lastly, I wanted to talk a little bit about IO202,

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:50.960
which is an anti-LIL-RB4 monoclonal antibody. So, LIL-RB4 is an inhibitory checkpoint receptor

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:56.320
that's highly expressed on neoplastic monocytes, and importantly also on monocytic blast equivalents,

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:06.320
pro-monocytes and monoblasts. So this antibody depletes LIL-RB4 positive cells through antibody

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:14.000
dependent cytotoxicity and antibody dependent phagocytosis. It was investigated in CMML patients

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:20.560
in part 2b of the phase one trial that was actually done at MD Anderson with Dr. DiNardo

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.800
and in combination with azacitidine in 21 HMA-naive CMML patients.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:34.080
The CR rate was around 30% and the overall response rate was nearly 70%. The reduction in

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:40.720
monocyte count was quite rapid. The medium time to response was one cycle, and it was fairly well

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:45.840
tolerated as well. And what was interesting here is that there were improved responses with higher

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:54.480
LIL-RB4 expression. There was also some pretty significant reductions in MPN-SAF symptom scores,

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:07.440
and this drug was efficacious seemingly in patients with ASXL1 mutations. And so about

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:15.760
70% of patients had ASXL1 mutations in this trial. And also of the three KRAS-mutated patients,

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:21.440
three of them actually cleared their KRAS mutations, which is pretty remarkable.

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:26.640
These are other ongoing CMML trials. So this is becoming more and more common,

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:30.960
so I think we're going to see more of this in the future, and hopefully we can

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:37.360
kind of improve outcomes for this porous leukemia going forward. Thank you.
